 sites, monetizing sites, SEO or getting traffic and so on. Along the way, we built

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:08.520
 a handful of other side projects.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:13.720
 But the main thing where PICFU came from is that we, being a team of two,

00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:19.720
 we kept having disagreements about design decisions, like both of us are

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:24.280
 software engineers and so, you know, without a ton of design experience.

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:28.240
 And so, his, you know, his guess was as good as mine and my guess was as good

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:31.760
 as his and every time we would butt heads, we'd ask our friends and family

00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:35.040
 for feedback and, you know, that they would be, we knew that they would be

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:38.880
 biased and, at some point, they kind of got tired of giving feedback, you know.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:45.120
 And so, when faced with the problem of trying to get unbiased feedback,

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:48.600
 we did what software engineers do, which is we built a tool.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:54.400
 So, we built a tool to get us unbiased feedback on our design decisions.

00:03:54.400 --> 00:04:00.440
 Logos, you know, logos, page layouts, marketing copy, collateral, all of that stuff.

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:02.640
 And we just kind of put it on the side.

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:07.040
 I think we put like a PayPal button on it, posted it to a handful of communities,

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:09.200
 but continued working on our main project.

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:12.640
 And that went on for a couple of years.

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:16.560
 And every, every couple of months or so, we would check in and we saw

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:21.320
 that PICFU was growing, you know, hey, more and more people found it.

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:22.960
 You can see people seem to like it.

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:25.840
 And then we'd go back to our main, then we'd go back to our main project.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.600
 A couple more months passed, we'd check again, same thing.

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:31.960
 Oh, now it's showing up and being used in other verticals as well.

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:32.840
 That's fascinating.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:35.240
 And then we'd focus on the main project again.

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:39.800
 And so eventually, after a couple iterations of that, we realized that, you know,

00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:47.280
 despite our best wishes, the traction on our main project was not going where we wanted it to go.

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:49.120
 And the traction on PICFU was growing.

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:54.280
 And so we decided to make up pivot there in terms of focusing our efforts,

00:04:54.280 --> 00:04:56.320
 our time and energy on PICFU and growing it.

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:58.560
 And that's what we've been doing ever since.

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:03.560
 Yeah, it's funny how building a product to solve a problem that you can't find a good solution

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:07.400
 to tends to be a good way of identifying problems that need solving.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:12.080
 Yeah, when, yeah, when you're, I guess the easiest way to build something

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:16.200
 that people might want is to start looking at your own problems first,

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:17.040
 solving those.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:19.400
 And maybe if that's a big enough problem that you're solving,

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:23.520
 then that solution could prove useful for other people too.

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:28.720
 So obviously you take testing seriously, how do you feel that the testing fits

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:33.520
 into the process of building a startup, building a company of any sort?

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:39.400
 I think that, I think that testing assumptions,

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:42.680
 and, you know, there's a phrase we use like test before you invest,

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:49.080
 like testing your assumptions, testing your hypotheses not only potentially lead

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:55.560
 to better outcomes, but they reduce a lot of downside risk.

00:05:55.560 --> 00:05:59.920
 So I see it, it's kind of like the two aren't exactly the same, right?

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:03.880
 Like you can't test a hypothesis and prove that it's going to skyrocket.

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:05.560
 Like it's going to be a rocket ship.

00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:08.280
 But you can very quickly, and if you can test,

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:12.640
 you can very quickly disprove a hypothesis about, oh, well, you know,

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:15.200
 I think that this kind of marketing, this kind of marketing message

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:17.640
 towards this audience is going to be the thing that resonates,

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:20.880
 or this kind of product feature or this kind of product benefit

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:24.880
 towards this potential target customer set is going to resonate or not.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:28.880
 If you can test that out before you actually commit it to whether it's code

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:33.680
 or print or publication or whatnot, then you improve your chances

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:36.640
 of having a better outcome for that project.

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:39.040
 Right. Yeah. The more ways that you can fail,

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:42.200
 you eliminate before you spend money, the better off you are.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:48.000
 Do you have any examples of cases where your testing and experimentation

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.160
 led to important effort savings or failed directions

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:56.080
 or made a critical impact on your path?

00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:58.280
 Yeah, on our path or on our customers?

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:00.320
 On yours, but or your customers.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:03.000
 Sure. I mean, we've definitely helped a lot of customers

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.760
 and some of the biggest names in e-commerce as well.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:10.320
 There was one company where we work with a lot of people

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:14.800
 who sell on Amazon and there was a company named Thrasio

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:19.000
 where they had a business which was to buy up individual Amazon shops

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.880
 and then optimize their, optimize their offerings,

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:24.920
 like their listings and then their products and so on.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:27.520
 And so there is this one product called Angry Orange.

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:29.320
 It was a pet deodorizing product.

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:30.920
 It worked really well.

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:34.200
 You know, it worked really well, but it, the design on the bottle

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:36.400
 and everything else was kind of subpar.

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:42.160
 And so the theory, the thesis behind that the Thrasio team had

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:46.560
 was that they could purchase this listing, rebrand the product,

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:48.600
 rebrand the bottle and do everything.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:50.640
 Don't change the composition of the product at all

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.160
 and that it could do better.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:56.200
 So the decision that they faced was that, that rebranding,

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:58.920
 they actually went through about 300 different designs

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.200
 for the rebranding process.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:06.760
 And the one that they wanted involved a $50,000 production

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:08.720
 design change because they wanted an orange bottle

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:11.280
 because the product was named Angry Orange.

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:14.000
 They wanted it to pop in the listings and on the store shelves

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:14.920
 and everything.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:18.920
 And so to justify that decision, that go no go decision,

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:21.120
 they went to take food and ran about six poles,

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:27.000
 cost about $500 in total pulled about 200 to 300 people.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.320
 So they got those results in about three days.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:34.240
 And those results validated that, yes, not just did,

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:38.000
 not only did the design that they wanted to go with,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.160
 beat out the original design, they'd also beat out

00:08:40.160 --> 00:08:42.360
 all the other variations that they were considering.

00:08:42.360 --> 00:08:45.320
 So those tests gave them the confidence

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:48.360
 to pull the trigger on that rebranding decision.

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:49.880
 And then they pulled the trigger on it.

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:52.320
 And the day after they relaunched the product

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:55.480
 on Amazon with the new packaging and everything else,

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:58.080
 their sales 10xed overnight.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:00.760
 So it went from a $2 million a year brand

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:05.920
 to a $19.5 million a year listing purely

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:10.240
 on the basis of the rebranding, full marketing rebrand

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:12.880
 and the packaging and everything else.

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:15.880
 That just took to show how much of the decision making

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:18.320
 that we do, we like to pretend that we're

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:19.760
 rational about these things.

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:23.160
 But the packaging to look, the feel, the name,

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:25.520
 all those things matter so much.

